[When the Clock Strikes]]'' (1961) (HF/UA)\n* ''[[You Have to Run Fast]]'' (1961) (HF/UA)\n* ''[[The Greengage Summer]]'' (1961) (PKL/Columbia)\n* ''[[Beauty and the Beast (1962 film)|Beauty and the Beast]]'' (1962) (HF/UA)\n* ''[[The Clown and the Kid]]'' (1962) (HF/UA)\n* ''[[Deadly Duo (1962 film)|Deadly Duo]]'' (1962) (HF/UA)\n* ''[[Gun Street]]'' (1962) (HF/UA)\n* ''[[Incident in an Alley]]'' (1962) (HF/UA)\n* ''[[Jack the Giant Killer (1962 film)|Jack the Giant Killer]]'' (1962) (Z/UA)\n* ''[[Saintly Sinners]]'' (1962) (HF/UA)\n* ''[[Tower of London (1962 film)|Tower of London]]'' (1962) (Admiral/UA)\n* ''[[Diary of a Madman (film)|Diary of a Madman]]'' (1963) (Admiral/UA)\n* ''[[Twice-Told Tales (film)|Twice Told Tales]]'' (1963) (Admiral/UA)\n* ''[[I'll Take Sweden]]'' (1965) (ES/UA)\n* ''[[Boy, Did I Get a Wrong Number!]]'' (1966) (ES/UA)\n* ''[[Frankie and Johnny (1966 film)|Frankie and Johnny]]'' (1966) (UA)\n* ''[[The Wicked Dreams of Paula Schultz]]'' (1968) (ES/UA)\n* ''[[The File of the Golden Goose]]'' (1969) (CP/UA)\n* ''[[The Christine Jorgensen Story]]'' (1970) (Eprod/UA)\n{{col-end}}\n\n:*ASR = Asher Small Rogers\n:*C = Columbia\n:*CP = Caralan Productions\n:*ES = Edward Small Productions\n:*FN = First National\n:*HF = Harvard Film Corporation\n:*R = Reliance\n:*UA = United Artists\n:*Z = Zenith Pictures\n\n===Unmade Films===\n{{div col|colwidth=40em}}\n* ''The Painted Face'' by [[Bayard Veiller]] (1928)<ref name=\"Times19280323\" />\n* ''The Broadway Melody'' (1929)<ref>\"Paramount Makes Silent Film: Alice Day to Play Lead in First National's \"Drag;\" Fox Follies Not Mere Revue-Will Have Story; E. H. Griffith Signing With Columbia\" Kingsley, Grace. ''Los Angeles Times'' 15 Mar 1929: A10.</ref>\n* first talking movie for [[Nazimova]] (1929)<ref>\"She'll Set Vogue in Voice Films\". ''Los Angeles Times'' 22 Apr 1929: A1.</ref>\n* ''Sojourn'' (1930)<ref>\"Shearer Film Ultra in Plot: \"Divorce\" Draws Crowds to Criterion Star's Effort Surpassing One on Talk Screen Excellent Supporting Cast Seen in Feature\" Schallert, Edwin. ''Los Angeles Times'' 16 May 1930: A9.</ref>\n* ''The Cradle of Jazz'' (1929) directed by Ted Wilde<ref>\"New Drama Arrives at Mayan Soon: Helen Menken Has Leading Role in New Play \"Top O' The Hill\" \"\n''Los Angeles Times'' 17 June 1929: A7.</ref> \u2013 stopped by Wilde's death from an old war wound in 1929 while directing a play for Small<ref>\"Apoplexy Fatal to Film Director: Rites for Ted Wilde Tomorrow \u2013 Masons to be in Charge of Services for Director Who Died Unexpectedly\" ''Los Angeles Times'' 18 Dec 1929: A7.</ref>\n* sequel to ''McFadden's Flats'' (1929)<ref>\"Duffy to Return in Mystery: \"Cat and Canary\" Listed at President; Dale Winter Costars in Play\". ''Los Angeles Times'' 25 Dec 1929: A11.</ref>\n* ''Mayor Harding of New York'' (1932) \u2013 abandoned after protests<ref>\"Noted Director Also Sculptor\" ''Los Angeles Times'' 10 Sep 1932: A7.</ref>\n* ''Style'' (1932) from a story by Adela Harland set in the fashion industry to star [[Lilyan Tashman]]<ref>\"Herbert Mundin Enjoys His Job in 'Cavalcade': Grows Red Whiskers to Play the Butler.\" Shaffer, George. ''Chicago Daily Tribune'' 30 Sep 1932: 19.</ref><ref name=\"chicago\" />\n* ''If Christ Came to Chicago'' (1933)<ref name=\"chicago\">''United Artists a Little Ahead for The Time of Year\" ''The Washington Post'' 12 Feb 1933: S5.</ref>\n* ''Mr Helen Green'' (1933)<ref name=\"chicago\"/>\n* untitled film with [[Lawrence Tibbett]]<ref>\"Success of Song Features Results in Five-Picture Offer for Lawrence Tibbett: Big Plans Ahead for Famous Opera Singer Walter Wanger Out to Sign Formidable Group of Movie Names; \"The Great Ziegfeld\" Not to Start Until November\" Schallert, Edwin. ''Los Angeles Times'' 25 Sep 1934: 19.</ref> \u2013 cancelled because Tibbett insisted on story and cast approval<ref>\"Broadway: Men and Maids.\" by Ed Sullivan. ''The Washington Post'' 5 May 1936: 16.</ref>\n* ''Beau Brummell'' (1934) with [[Robert Donat]]<ref>\"Eight Music Publishers in International Tie-up for Expected Opera Cycle: Meyer Appointed to Negotiate All Sales Fay Wray Wins Star Role in \"Mills of the Gods;\" Selznick Signs Clemence Dane; Joe Morrison in \"Win or Lose\" \"Scheuer, Philip K. ''Los Angeles Times'' 8 Oct 1934: 15.</ref>\n* ''Lusitania'' (1935)<ref name=\"vital\">\"Timeliness Declared Vital in Selecting Story Plots\" ''Los Angeles Times'' 7 Aug 1935: 12.</ref>\n* ''Amateur Girl'' (1935) with Constance Cummings and Robert Young<ref name=\"bell\">\"United Artists, Despite the Loss of Twentieth Century, Sees Big Season Ahead: Many Pictures Scheduled for Early Release British Studios Help Out; At Circus Coincidence; Amusement Jottings. (Reprinted from Yesterday's Last Edition.)\" by Nelson B. Bell.. ''The Washington Post'' 14 June 1935: 20.</ref>\n* ''David Garrick'' (1935)<ref>\"Announces New Films: Reliance Studios Executive Tells of Year's Plans.\" ''New York Times'' 22 Aug 1935: 20.</ref>\n* ''The Mark of [[Zorro]]'' (1935)<ref name=\"doug\"/> \u2013 later (1953) with Anthony Dexter<ref>\"Looking at Hollywood: Glenn Ford Is Scheduled to Make Picture, 'The Americano,' in Brazil\" Hopper, Hedda. ''Chicago Daily Tribune'' 30 Mar 1953: b6.</ref>\n* ''Yosesmite'' (1935) \u2013 Western from script by Philip Dunne<ref>\"Walter Connoolly Summoned East to Play Lead in \"Soak the Rich\" Picture: Player to Work for Hecht, MacArthur Edward Small Will Star George Houston in Saga of California Indians; Rudy Vallee to Stay in East for Next Production\" Schallert, Edwin. ''Los Angeles Times'' 28 Sep 1935: 5.</ref>\n* ''Robin Hood'' (1935) with [[Robert Donat]]<ref name=\"bell\"/>\n* adaptation of ''[[The Beggar's Opera]]'' (1935)<ref>\"First American Cinema Version of \"Beggar's Opera\" Planned by Reliance: Houston Mentioned as Chief Character Joan Bennett Will Emote Opposite Ronald Colman in \"Man Who Broke the Bank;\" William Powell Film Announced\" Scheuer, Philip K. ''Los Angeles Time